## 2.5.3 Linear Propagator Models

### Purpose

Place the OW model inside the broader class of linear propagator models.

### Setup / formulation

A general linear propagator model has impact:

$$
I_t = \int_0^t G(t,s)dQ_s,
$$

where $G(t,s)$ is a decay kernel.

The OW model is the special case:

$$
G(t,s) = \lambda e^{-\beta(t-s)}.
$$

### Main result

General propagator kernels capture richer empirical decay patterns but often lose the simple Markovian and myopic structure of OW.

### Interpretation

The OW model is tractable because exponential decay makes $I_t$ a state variable satisfying a one-dimensional SDE.

More general kernels may fit data better but usually require:

- Higher-dimensional state representations.
- Numerical methods.
- Approximation by sums of exponentials.
- Additional no-manipulation checks.

