## 2.6.4 Global Concavity

### Purpose

Discuss globally concave impact models, especially the AFS model, and contrast them with local concavity.

### Setup / formulation

Global concavity applies at the aggregate impact level, not just the microscopic fill level.

The AFS-style model uses a nonlinear mapping between cumulative impact and trades.

A reduced-form representation uses a transformed impact variable, often denoted through a function of the impact state.

### Main result

Globally concave models can capture empirical concavity of metaorder impact, but they are structurally different from locally concave OW extensions.

The PDF treats global concavity as a reduced-form model rather than deriving it fully from the same microscopic assumptions as local concavity.

### Interpretation

Local and global concavity should not be confused.

- Local concavity concerns individual microscopic trades or short-time increments.
- Global concavity concerns aggregate impact over a larger order.
- The two lead to different mathematics and different control problems.

Global concavity is useful empirically but can be less tractable than generalized OW.

