## 2.7.3 Constraints on Volume Predictions

### Purpose

Translate price-manipulation constraints into practical restrictions on predicted market volume.

### Setup / formulation

Suppose liquidity scales with predicted volume $v_t$.

For a square-root-style scaling:

$$
\lambda_t \propto v_t^{-1/2}.
$$

Then:

$$
\gamma_t' = -\frac{1}{2}\frac{v_t'}{v_t}.
$$

The no-manipulation condition becomes:

$$
2\beta_t - \frac{1}{2}\frac{v_t'}{v_t} > 0.
$$

Equivalently:

$$
\frac{v_t'}{v_t} < 4\beta_t.
$$

If $\beta$ is constant, the minimum volume doubling time implied by this inequality is:

$$
\Delta t > \frac{\log 2}{4\beta}.
$$

Since the impact half-life is:

$$
\frac{\log 2}{\beta},
$$

the volume doubling time must exceed one quarter of the impact half-life.

### Main result

Volume predictions cannot increase too quickly relative to impact decay.

Rapidly increasing volume forecasts can create manipulation opportunities in the model.

### Interpretation

This is the chapter’s most practical no-manipulation takeaway.

A volume curve used in an execution algorithm is not harmless. If the predicted market activity rises too sharply, the implied liquidity improvement may let the model generate artificial profits through round trips.

Negative liquidity shocks are asymmetric: they make trading expensive but do not create the same manipulation mechanism.

